default&#xa0;defaultHow robust are the conclusions in the AR5 Physical Science Basis report?defaultThe Government considers that the conclusions of the AR5 Physi
defaultcal Science Basis report are robust.  The report was produced by over 850 independent expert scientists, all leaders in their fields (209 Lead Authors, 50 Review Editors and Over 600 Contributing Authors).  The report took over 2 years to produce and under
defaultwent multiple rounds of expert review.  It was also reviewed by the 194 governments which form the IPCC.  They have all accepted the findings.   
defaultIPCC reports 
defaultaim to assess the available literature and draw conclusions based on the full range of evidence. 
default Some individual conclusions will be more robust than others depending on the state of scientific knowledge in a particular area.
default  
defaultThe Physical Science Basis report cite
defaults
default more than 9,200 scientific publications
default and employs defined language to describe the 
defaultavailability of evidence (e.g. limited, medium or robust) and the degree of agreement of the evidence (e.g. low, medium, high).  Similarly defined language is used to describe both the level of confidence in a finding and the likelihood of an outcome or re
defaultsult occurring.  The use of this defined uncertainty language allowed the Physical Science Basis report to communicate clearly and directly the range of certainty in the scientific evidence and confidence in the conclusions drawn. 
